post_text:
Congratulations to Vivian Kin (Crossroads South) who has been selected as the grand prize winner of the New Jersey Coalition for Inclusive Education 2019-2020 Inclusion Works Poster Contest.

President and CEO Fred Buglione of the New Jersey Coalition for Inclusive Educators wrote that her poster "portrayed multiple aspects of inclusion by welcoming physical disabilities and all students' abilities, and it is diverse and representative of multiple communities. The statement, "We are less when we don't include everyone", is inspiring, powerful and a great example of why inclusion works."

Printed copies of Vivian's "Inclusion Works" poster will be distributed to schools throughout New Jersey. Her poster will also be placed on NJCIE’s website and social media for schools across the country during the 2020-21 school year.

Way to go Vivian!

INDIAN FIELDS THANKS ESSENTIAL WORKERS...
Art Teachers and Counselors at Indian Fields had a conversation about working together to thank essential workers who had been helping all of us stay safe and well during this time of Covid-19. They met with Administrators to plan how to accomplish this goal and decided to co-teach lessons to K-5 students on Gratitude during virtual lessons, and offer students and staff the opportunity to make pieces of artwork to express their gratitude. After everyone made their beautiful artwork, they collected the pictures and created a video to share with essential workers, organizations and businesses in our community. Please click on the following link to view the video that is sure to put a smile on your face.

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1FFxdrX4HC4jBzxklFLXq83399kGKx1jj/view

post_text:
Help us celebrate the Class of 2020 and show them just how special they are to us by placing the attached sign in your windows!! We are attaching three different versions of the sign - one colored, one grayscale and one that students can color themselves. We ask the South Brunswick Community to send our seniors off with all of the well wishes that they deserve by placing a version of the sign in your front windows..

Feel free to share the signs with neighbors and local stores so when the Class of 2020 are out and about they can see just how loved they are and that they will always be South Brunswick Vikings!!

The festival will broadcast LIVE on Tuesday, May 12th at 7 PM on the VTN YouTube Channel, https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCIkHl3_hBy1beY0KG5nb6Ig/live
Premiering films in a variety of categories written and directed by our very own SB students! We hope all students & staff will tune in, as it is sure to be a fun family movie night!

All SB students and staff will have the opportunity to vote for up to 3 of their favorite films. The voting window will open immediately following the event, and will close shortly after the 7 PM replay set to air on Wednesday, May 13th. The winners will be announced on May 14th at 10:00 am!

Want a sneak peek at the films that will premiere?
Check out the Event Program, https://online.flippingbook.com/view/481509/

Watch our Trailer, https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qwvNCyYqkyk&feature=youtu.be

Grab some popcorn and don’t miss this amazing virtual event!
Visit sbtechstorm.weebly.com for more details.

post_text: NJ Mental Health Cares, the state’s behavioral health information and referral service, will now also offer help to people dealing with anxiety and worry related to the Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak. New Jerseyans can call 1-866-202-HELP (4357) for free, confidential support. NJ Mental Health Cares will be answered from 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. seven days a week by live trained specialists. For the latest medical information, including mental health guidance and tips, visit the Centers for Disease Control’s website: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prepare/managing-stress-anxiety.html.

March 27th is International SEL Day!
March 27 is International SEL (Social Emotional Learning) Day. Teaching our students how to be mindful and aware of their feelings, and to respectfully interact with others, is a priority of our district. The link below shows our district’s plan to increase SEL skills, and show the “competencies” we want our students to demonstrate. During this time of remote learning, we will continue to emphasize the importance of taking care of ourselves and others, being problem solvers, and communicating even when we can’t all be together right now!

post_text:
The South Brunswick Office of Emergency Management is coordinating with South Brunswick Social Services to address the needs of township residents during these difficult times.

There will be a food drive from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. on Friday, March 20 at police headquarters, 540 Ridge Road, Monmouth Junction, to help fill the food pantry shelves.

Needed items include canned or dried soups; canned or dry beans; pasta and sauce; canned vegetables; canned meats such as tuna, chicken and SPAM; canned pasta; cereal and oatmeal; peanut butter and jelly; shelf stable milk; rice; canned tomatoes; boxed or canned potatoes; and macaroni and cheese.

Gift cards to Stop & Shop and ShopRite are greatly appreciated.

The South Brunswick Schools will continue remote learning and the buildings will be closed from Monday, March 16th - Friday, March 20th. The District closure includes all after-school activities, trips, athletics, PTO and Education Foundation events. This decision was made after thoughtful
consultation with our partner state agencies and further information regarding the Governor’s plans shared today at his 2:00 pm press conference, where he shared that school closures are just days away. Please click on the following link to view a message from our Superintendent of Schools, Scott Feder.

Chartwells will host three sites in the township where students can pick up a brown bag breakfast and lunch. Please review the pickup sites below and the schools that each site will support.

Join us in congratulating, Diana Kwiatkowski, a member of our Community Education family who retired Friday, February 28, after 40 yrs in the District. Diana started as a Chartwells employee and then joined the South Brunswick Community Education Department in the Before and After School Program at Brunswick Acres for the last 29.5 yrs.

She will definitely be missed ! Congratulations Diana!!

(pictured (left to right) Jennifer Minaya-Osemwegie, Director of Community Education, Diana and Kelli Williams-Stackhouse)

post_text: It’s" Are You Happy" time at SBHS. "Are You Happy" was created to bring about awareness for our students and community who may be suffering from bipolar disorder, OCD, depression, anxiety, generalized anxiety or any other mental health condition. It’s a simple sign to read and ask yourself out loud “Are you happy?” Resources are listed for students. Early identification is key for the best mental health outcomes.
